QID73_TEXT: We know that regular physical exercise can keep people healthy.  Even if an individual or community doesn't exercise per se, just being able to walk on a regular basis can improve health.  In communities where it's easy to walk, like where there's sidewalks, playgrounds, parks, grass, trees-- people feel more inclined to walk compared to areas that are not "walk friendly" and where walking may even be not safe.  Those communities suffer from higher rates of obesity, heart stresses, and other factors arising from a sedentary lifestyle.  We find by simply making a community "walk-friendly" we enhance the health and well-being of that community and it spends less money on medical needs because more people will engage in walking.
QID74_1: Enhancing a community's walkability has multiple long-term health benefits.
QID74_2: We can save on medical costs simply by making neighborhoods more walkable.
QID74_3: People may avoid exercise, but most humans will engage in walking if their community supports it and has safe and attractive areas for such.  It's also social: the more people you see walking, the more likely you are to do the same thing.

QID73_TEXT: That it is a good thing to reduce the amount of meat eaten.  It is not necessary to go fully vegetarian -- it can also really help to pledge to eat less meat overall.  There are so many alternatives currently available that it is easy to make this change and reduce the amount of meat consumed.  Not only is it healthier for one to eat less meat (reducing the amount of bad fats ingested) but it is also far better for the environment to reduce the number of animals raised for food.  A great deal of the agricultural products grown today are used to feed food animals, which is not the best use of produce.  The animals themselves also do damage to the environment, particularly cattle who emit (fart) a great deal of methane gas which is a proven component of what is causing climate change.  And, of course, animals raised for food are not treated humanely and we are forced to deal with our consciences where this is concerned.  Is it ethical and morally right to treat animals this way?  Some conditions are just deplorable -- some pigs are kept in crates so small that they cannot even turn around.  The message is getting out about this and the environmental consequences of meat eating -- and people are reducing their intake of meat.
